{"comments":"Euler angles with rotation order for 3D rotations.\n\n## Proof References\nAll operations correspond to proven theorems in `proofs/Hydrogen/Math/Euler.lean`:\n- toQuaternion_zeroWithOrder: Zero Euler → identity quaternion (all orders)\n- toMat3_zeroWithOrder: Zero Euler → identity Mat3 (all orders)\n- toMat4_zeroWithOrder: Zero Euler → identity Mat4 (all orders)\n- neg_neg: Double negation is identity\n- neg_preserves_order: Negation preserves rotation order\n- toVec3_fromVec3: Vec3 round-trip is identity\n\n## Three.js Parity\n- All six rotation orders: XYZ, YZX, ZXY, XZY, YXZ, ZYX\n- Intrinsic Tait-Bryan angles (local coordinate rotations)\n- Conversion to/from quaternions and matrices\n\n## Why Euler Angles\nEuler angles are intuitive for humans (pitch, yaw, roll) but suffer from\ngimbal lock. For interpolation and composition, convert to Quaternion.\n\n## Mathematical Background\nEuler angles represent rotation as three successive rotations about\ncoordinate axes. The rotation order matters: XYZ ≠ ZYX.\n\nFor intrinsic rotations (Three.js convention), rotations are applied\nwith respect to the local (rotating) coordinate system. In matrix form:\nM_XYZ = Rz(z) × Ry(y) × Rx(x)\n","declarations":[{"children":[{"comments":null,"info":{"arguments":[],"declType":"dataConstructor"},"sourceSpan":{"end":[108,8],"name":"../../hydrogen/src/Hydrogen/Schema/Dimension/Rotation/Euler.purs","start":[108,3]},"title":"XYZ"},{"comments":null,"info":{"arguments":[],"declType":"dataConstructor"},"sourceSpan":{"end":[109,8],"name":"../../hydrogen/src/Hydrogen/Schema/Dimension/Rotation/Euler.purs","start":[109,3]},"title":"YZX"},{"comments":null,"info":{"arguments":[],"declType":"dataConstructor"},"sourceSpan":{"end":[110,8],"name":"../../hydrogen/src/Hydrogen/Schema/Dimension/Rotation/Euler.purs","start":[110,3]},"title":"ZXY"},{"comments":null,"info":{"arguments":[],"declType":"dataConstructor"},"sourceSpan":{"end":[111,8],"name":"../../hydrogen/src/Hydrogen/Schema/Dimension/Rotation/Euler.purs","start":[111,3]},"title":"XZY"},{"comments":null,"info":{"arguments":[],"declType":"dataConstructor"},"sourceSpan":{"end":[112,8],"name":"../../hydrogen/src/Hydrogen/Schema/Dimension/Rotation/Euler.purs","start":[112,3]},"title":"YXZ"},{"comments":null,"info":{"arguments":[],"declType":"dataConstructor"},"sourceSpan":{"end":[113,8],"name":"../../hydrogen/src/Hydrogen/Schema/Dimension/Rotation/Euler.purs","start":[113,3]},"title":"ZYX"},{"comments":null,"info":{"declType":"instance","dependencies":[],"type":{"annotation":[],"contents":[{"annotation":[],"contents":[["Data","Eq"],"Eq"],"tag":"TypeConstructor"},{"annotation":[],"contents":[["Hydrogen","Schema","Dimension","Rotation","Euler"],"RotationOrder"],"tag":"TypeConstructor"}],"tag":"TypeApp"}},"sourceSpan":{"end":[115,52],"name":"../../hydrogen/src/Hydrogen/Schema/Dimension/Rotation/Euler.purs","start":[115,1]},"title":"eqRotationOrder"},{"comments":null,"info":{"declType":"instance","dependencies":[],"type":{"annotation":[],"contents":[{"annotation":[],"contents":[["Data","Show"],"Show"],"tag":"TypeConstructor"},{"annotation":[],"contents":[["Hydrogen","Schema","Dimension","Rotation","Euler"],"RotationOrder"],"tag":"TypeConstructor"}],"tag":"TypeApp"}},"sourceSpan":{"end":[123,19],"name":"../../hydrogen/src/Hydrogen/Schema/Dimension/Rotation/Euler.purs","start":[117,1]},"title":"showRotationOrder"}],"comments":"The six possible rotation orders for Euler angles.\nEach order specifies which axis to rotate around first, second, third.\nThree.js uses intrinsic rotations (local coordinate system).\n\nProof reference: Euler.lean RotationOrder\n","info":{"dataDeclType":"data","declType":"data","roles":[],"typeArguments":[]},"kind":null,"sourceSpan":{"end":[113,8],"name":"../../hydrogen/src/Hydrogen/Schema/Dimension/Rotation/Euler.purs","start":[107,1]},"title":"RotationOrder"},{"children":[{"comments":null,"info":{"arguments":[{"annotation":[],"contents":[["Prim"],"Number"],"tag":"TypeConstr